{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509741"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11438"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11438"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.8,0.1,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"20668"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4072"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"9874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4316"},{"type":"tags","id":"4639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"20668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/20668"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner after noticing a lesion on his penis. He first noticed it about a week ago, with minimal progression in the time. There is no pain or pruritus associated with the lesion. He is sexually active and does not use barrier contraception. In the past six months, he has had sexual intercourse with three female partners. He does not take any medications and his medical history is unremarkable. His immunisations are up-to-date. Currently, his vital signs are normal and the patient looks well on general observation. Genital examination shows a single painless, superficial ulcer with indurated borders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Condyloma acuminatum","Chancre","Herpes simplex virus II","Trichomonas vaginalis","Chancroid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echancre\u003C/strong\u003E is a clinical presentation of primary syphilis (early manifestation). It presents with a painless papule with a flat top. The incidence of syphilis in Australia is increasing. There is a high prevalence in men who have sex with men and remote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities. The prevalence is also increasing in the general population, especially in women of reproductive age. Syphilis in pregnant people has led to the re-emergence of congenital syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondyloma acuminatum\u003C/strong\u003E is a lesion caused by HPV. While the lesion is painless, it usually presents as clusters of raised lesions with a verrucous surface. verrucous surface. Application of 3-5% acetic acid can be used which turns dysplastic and neoplastic tissue lesions white; this is not a specific test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHSV II, Trichomonas vaginalis, and chancroid are all painful lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV II\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with multiple vesicles on an erythematous base.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/strong\u003E is asymptomatic in males and presents as cervicitis (\u0022strawberry cervix\u0022) in females.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemophilus ducreyi (\u003Cstrong\u003Echancroid\u003C/strong\u003E) is extremely painful and exudates in the centre of the papule.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chancre is a painless genital ulcer most commonly formed during the primary stage of syphilis."],"references":["Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. 2015 Sexually Transmitted Diseases Treatment Guidelines: Gonococcal Infections. https://www.cdc.gov/std/tg2015/gonorrhea.htm","UpToDate. Uptodate.com. Published 2022. Accessed January 27, 2022. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/approach-to-the-patient-with-genital-ulcers","\u200cTopic | Therapeutic Guidelines. Bond.edu.au. Published 2021. Accessed January 27, 2022. https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.ezproxy.bond.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=syphilis\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e47","Syphilis - STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. STI Guidelines Australia. 2021 [cited 2022 Feb 7]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/syphilis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"9874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11438"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"9874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/9874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-02-08T09:44:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-02-08T09:44:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4072"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"20668"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonym